}</style><div class="truncate-component js-truncate-component--abstract"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">Trust concern among customers and a company is the most important factor for a company to be successful. For many years businesses have used different types of systems and applications to build a relationship with their customers. For this purpose, the Customer Relationship Management (CRM) tool is the most popular application companies are using. This tool utilizes the approaches and the strategies which the company needs to take to serve a customer. As a result of technological advances, there is a great opportunity now for companies to use the latest features in their CRM systems and enhance customer interaction with their businesses. In this dissertation, monolithic and modern technology-based design in the CRM application domain is discussed, showing the benefits of each and explaining why companies are being encouraged to reconsider existing legacy monolithic CRM systems in relation to modern technologies.</p><div class="toggle-truncation-button js-toggle-truncation-button--abstract"><button class="safe-abstract--toggle-truncation-button"><span>... </span><span class="safe-abstract--toggle-truncation-button-text">Read more</span></button></div></div></div></div><div class="safe-figure-carousel-section--container"><div class="safe-figure-carousel-section--heading" id="figures">Figures (28)</div><div class="safe-figure-carousel--container"><div class="carousel-container js-figure-carousel carousel-container--md" id="loswp-figures"><div class="prev-slide-container js-prev-button-container"><button aria-label="Previous" class="carousel-navigation-button js-loswp-figures-prev"><span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 24px" translate="no">arrow_back_ios</span></button></div><div class="slides-container js-slides-container"><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324472/table-1-monolithic-architecture-vs-multi-layered-cloud-based"><img alt="" class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/table_001.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs"></figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324202/figure-1-in-the-case-of-an-application-monolithic-design-is"><img alt="In the case of an application, a monolithic design is a single piece of code or a deployable code artefact  an application that can and should be deployed on a single machine.? The layers in the programming domain refer to the logical separation of the codebase in the application.* The monolithic design has all the codebase in one layer, and it creates only one artefact to be deployed to other environments. Hence in monolithic applications, the majority of the code logic is deployed and executes on a centralized, single environment on a server. These types of applications are usually large applications and they have been created by a large team of developers. Making any new change in the monolithic application needs an organized orchestration among the developers to make sure the changes are not detrimental to each other. For this reason, updating the monolithic application is done less frequently and this is because of the delivery approach for the monolithic application. Once a version of a monolithic application is planned to be delivered, the whole application will be released, and it will be a large single deployment to the hosting server. Once the application has reached a certain size, it needs to be scaled. Figure 1 shows the scalability cube: " class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_001.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">In the case of an application, a monolithic design is a single piece of code or a deployable code artefact  an application