r structures of the system, which comprise software elements, the externally visible properties of those elements, and the relationships among them. From this definition, the layered architecture is regarded as an architectural pattern that organizes functionalities into different layers and logically separates the codes from each other.? Splitting the application into different layers is the common best practice pattern used in software architecture to break down complex systems. In the layered architecture, each component is arranged as a form of a layer cake, with each new layer placed as the lowest layer. Each layer includes grouped elements that provide related services. The higher layer can get service from the immediate lower layer (closed architecture) or all the lower layers (open architecture). The key here is that the lower layer has no dependency on the higher  layer and is unaware of it.1! 12 13 14 " class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_002.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">In this context, each layer is coherent and independent, and they have no knowledge about the other layers. Therefore, the implementation of each layer could be done in isolation, and different technologies can be used in each layer. The layers can communicate with each other via interfaces or RESTful APls. In this case, interfaces behave like a contract, where two layers agree to provide specific parameters to each other and receive the expected services and information. In nutshell, the  generic concept of three-tier architecture is as shown in Figure 2.  Bass, Clements and Kazman? define the software architecture of a program or computing system as the structure or structures of the system, which comprise software elements, the externally visible properties of those elements, and the relationships among them. From this definition, the layered architecture is rega