igure_003.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">In general, the multi-layered architecture of a CRM system can be demonstrated in all the modern CRM applications and specifically in the Salesforce CRM. By creating a multi-layered design all the components can talk to each other via interfaces/contracts or APIs. In modularized CRM this capability of having different modules can lead to having different business products, and each module can behave in isolation. In the Salesforce CRM model, there is the main and core platform that sits in the centre of the business CRM. The other CRM components, or any third-party application, communicate with the core CRM as shown in Figure 3.  Salesforce, like other companies, has heavily promoted cloud computing. In the fast-growing technological environment, Salesforce has kept growing and kept introducing different services accordingly. The separation model and keeping the tool in the cloud were key to Salesforces success and made businesses able to track their customers in a more manageable way. </figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324258/figure-5-sap-ui-integrating-with-different-application-the"><img alt="Figure 5: SAP UI Integrating with Different Application  The SAP software is made flexible by the provision of both cloud-based and on-premises solutions and the new UI tools are defined to enhance this aspect of the tool. SAP Fiori, Sap UIS5 and SAP GUI* are the three main programming languages used to create the user interfaces. Briefly, SAP UI5 is a JavaScript UI library that is used to create responsive Uls and specifically SAP Ul-friendly components, which is set to work with JavaScript, and this has been included in this library. Fiori Design is defining the specifications of the UX design model for all the SAP products. The output of this library is like a blueprint for how the UX should look. It can work with both cloud-based Uls and on-premises applications. The SAP GUI is a library that works with the on-premises UI applications and provides the elements and objects that can be used to design the user interface. To summarise, the UI technologies working with SAP applications in the different environments are as follow:  SAP Screen Personas is an SAP tool which handles the on-premises application and allows the user to personalize the SAP screen, the platform decides which tools needs to be run, and defines the components and objects. Similarly, the SAP web IDE built on top of the SAP Cloud Platform lets the developers build Ul screens depending on the platform on which the tool is going to be run. " class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_004.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">Figure 5: SAP UI Integrating with Different Application  The SAP software is made flexible by the provision of both cloud-based and on-premises solutions and the new UI tools are defined to enhance this aspect of the tool. SAP Fiori, Sap UIS5 and SAP GUI* are the three main programming languages used to create the user interfaces. Briefly, SAP UI5 is a JavaScript UI library that is used to create responsive Uls and specifically SAP Ul-friendly components, which is set to work with JavaScript, and this has been included in this library. Fiori Design is defining the specifications of the UX design model for all the SAP products. The output of this library is like a blueprint for how the UX should look. It can work with both cloud-based Uls and on-premises applications. The SAP GUI is a library that works with the on-premises UI applications and provides the elements and objects that can be used to design the user interface. To summarise, the UI technologies working with SAP applications in the different environments are as follow:  SAP Screen Personas is an SAP tool which handles the on-premises application and allows the user to personalize the SAP screen, the platform decides which tools needs to be run, and defines the components and objects. Similarly, the SAP web IDE built on top of the SAP Cloud Platform lets the developers build Ul screens depending on the platform on which the tool is going to be run. </figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324273/figure-6-onsidering-the-requirements-the-high-level-use-case"><img alt="onsidering the requirements, the high-level use-case diagram for the system is shown in Figure 6 " class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_005.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">onsidering the requirements, the high-level use-case diagram for the system is shown in Figure 6 </figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324286/figure-6-monolithic-architecture-vs-multi-layered-cloud"><img alt="" class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_006.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs"></figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324291/figure-7-the-class-in-is-monolith-class-which-holds"><img alt="The class in Figure 7, is a monolith class which holds implementation for customer update, order Update and communication functionalities. When it comes to interface segregation, mainly four different interfaces can be achieved from the monolith class. The ICommon interface has all the common functionalities and hence will be extended by the other interfaces. So, the point of interface segregation comes where the module which is going to be responsible for Customer related functionalities, will not have access to order related functionalities. More extension to this principle is, there is no matter how deep the separation can go and as far as the boundaries are been defined correctly, the monolith system with no change in the implementation can support different interfaces. " class="figure-slide-image" loading="eager" src="https://figures.academia-assets.com/61905259/figure_007.jpg" width="236" height="141" /></a><figcaption class="figure-slide-caption ds2-5-body-xs">The class in Figure 7, is a monolith class which holds implementation for customer update, order Update and communication functionalities. When it comes to interface segregation, mainly four different interfaces can be achieved from the monolith class. The ICommon interface has all the common functionalities and hence will be extended by the other interfaces. So, the point of interface segregation comes where the module which is going to be responsible for Customer related functionalities, will not have access to order related functionalities. More extension to this principle is, there is no matter how deep the separation can go and as far as the boundaries are been defined correctly, the monolith system with no change in the implementation can support different interfaces. </figcaption></figure><figure class="figure-slide-container"><a href="https://www.academia.edu/figures/13324298/figure-9-in-this-application-models-are-used-to-get-the"><img alt="In this application, models are used to get the necessary information to the pages, and some of the classes are just to hold the data and are used to group the properties altogether. And to follow the monolithic design, there is only once class to serve the requests with different methods. The main  class is shown in Figure 9.  This class is a set of public methods that handle the request from the user and redirect the request to the relevant method. The monolithic design lets all the functions stay in the same class to make it  much easier to track and develop the features. Thi